<figure class="post__image post__image--center"><img decoding="auto" loading="lazy"  src="https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/vemulator-logo.svg" alt="" width="377" height="88"></figure>
<p> </p>
<figure class="post__image post__image--right"><img decoding="auto" loading="lazy"  style="margin-bottom: 1.37143rem; margin-left: 1.37143rem; outline: 3px solid rgba(var(--color-primary-rgb), 0.55) !important;" src="https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/vemulator.png" alt="" width="1080" height="1080" sizes="(max-width: 1200px) 100vw, 1200px" srcset="https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/responsive/vemulator-xs.webp 300w ,https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/responsive/vemulator-sm.webp 480w ,https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/responsive/vemulator-md.webp 768w ,https://pixelnostalgia.github.io/media/posts/277/responsive/vemulator-xl.webp 1200w"></figure>
<p>The Visual Memory Unit is a memory card used by Sega's Dreamcast console. Unlike other memory cards, the VMU has a small LCD display and a set of buttons that resemble those on a Game Boy portable console. The VMU plugs directly into the joypad. During play, a small screen displays game information, pictures, and hints.<br><br>Some games, such as Sonic Adventure, allow you to copy special software to the VMU so that you can play the game without connecting to a console. In addition, the memory card allows you to see the current time thanks to the built-in clock. The VMU is available in several colors, the most common being blue (made of transparent blue plastic) and white.</p>

<h5>The package includes:</h5>
