<p>The Pecom 64 was a computer designed for education and home use in Serbia in the mid-1980s. It had a CDP 1802B processor, 32 KB of RAM, and a cassette tape for storage. It could display text and graphics on a TV screen, and produce sound through two channels. It had a programmable character set and a reconfigurable keyboard.<br><br>It was compatible with some software and hardware from other computers, such as the Cosmac VIP and the Commodore 64. It was one of the first computers made in Yugoslavia.</p>

